> 'Allo Genovese' simply means 'in the style of Genoa', which is the northern Italian
> city famous for the pesto that you'll be making tonight. 'Pesto' actually comes
> from the word 'pestare', which means to pound or crush, referring to the old
> fashioned method of making it in a pestle & mortar. If you happen to have a food
> processor, you can whizz the pesto together in that, or alternatively just chop,
> chop, chop everything until it is tiny. Andiamo!

Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} for your gnocchi. Peel and chop
@garlic clove{1/2}.

Heat a #frying pan{} up to the hob and add in the @pine nuts{4}. Allow the pine
nuts to toast (without oil). Keep cooking them until they are nicely browned off
on all sides - it takes a while but watch them carefully as the moment your back
is turned, they'll burn!

In a #pestle & mortar{}, put in the remaining @garlic clove{1/2} and grind with
a @salt{pinch}. Next, add in the @basil{25%g}(leaves) and keep grinding to a paste.
Now, grind in @pine nuts{3/4%of the above}. If you don't have a pestle & mortar,
simply chop the basil as finely as possible.

Turn the mixture out into a #bowl{} and add @grated hard Italian style cheese{1/2}.
Stir the mixture whilst drizzling in some @extra virgin olive oil{}. Keep drizzling
it in until you have a nice, runny consistency. Now add all but a sprinkle of the
@grated hard Italian style cheese{all but a sprinkle}.

Chop the @tenderstem broccoli{1}(widthways into 3 pieces). Plunge into the boiling
water for ~{1%minute} then remove and keep to the side. Keep the water for the gnocchi.

Place the @Del Verde fresh gnocchi{1%packet} in the water and cook for ~{4%minutes}.
Drain and keep to the side.

Whilst the gnocchi is cooking, bash the remaining garlic with the flat side of a
#knife{}. Add the garlic to a frying pan with @olive oil{1%tbsp} on medium-high
heat. Once the pan is nice and hot, add in the tenderstem broccoli and cook for
~{2%mins}. Season well with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Put the drained gnocchi in the pan with the tenderstem. Remove from the heat and
stir in your homemade pesto. Serve with a sprinkle of cheese and the remaining nuts.